 Synchronous and Asynchronous Programming are different approaches to writing code that handles time or performance differently.

1) Synchronous Programming: In this method, a program runs one task at a time. It completes the current task before moving onto another. JavaScript's synchronous execution happens in a single thread. When a function is called, it runs sequentially, and the control returns to the caller only after the completion of that specific function. The code below demonstrates how synchronous programming works:

```js
function A() {
  console.log("Function A starts");
  // Synchronous task
  const result = calculateSomething();
  console.log(`Result of Function A: ${result}`);
}

function B() {
  console.log("Function B starts");
  // Synchronous task
  let number = askForInput();
  console.log(`Number received by Function B: ${number}`);
}

A(); // Function A executes first, then moves to the next line when it's done
B(); // Function B will start after all tasks of Function A are completed
```

2) Asynchronous Programming: This programming method handles multiple tasks simultaneously by switching between them. JavaScript does this using callback functions or Promises. When a function executes asynchronously, the control returns to the caller immediately without waiting for its completion and then waits for a later callback, or Promise to be resolved before moving further.

```js
function A() {
  console.log("Function A starts");
  // Asynchronous task using call back
  setTimeout(function () {
    const result = calculateSomething();
    console.log(`Result of Function A: ${result}`);
  }, 2000);
}

function B() {
  console.log("Function B starts");
  // Asynchronous task using Promise
  let number = askForInput().then((input) => {
    console.log(`Number received by Function B: ${number}`);
  });
}

A(); // Function A executes immediately and will print "Function A starts", but the result won't be displayed until the timer is up.
B(); // Function B also starts immediately, and it won't wait for Function A to finish.
```

Note that while Node.js uses event loop and callbacks for asynchronous programming, in a browser, JavaScript uses Promises and Async/Await syntax for the same.

